Introduction

The goal of the project is to predict the exercise manner (or quality) of six participants based on a number of predictor variables. The outcome is stored in the classe variable of the training set. We will explore a several classifiers to solve this problem, notably random forest, gradient boosting, linear discriminant analysis, support vector machine, and k-nearest neighbour. Finally we will apply the final model to predict the 20 cases in the test set. We will further calculate the importance of the predictors (variables) based on our most successful model, and use the result of the importance to explore the underlying data.

Data import

Import required libraries, download data files, and use read_csv() to parse the csv files:

# Load required packages
library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
## Loading required package: ggplot2
library(readr)
library(corrplot)
## corrplot 0.84 loaded
# Download data files
download.file("https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-training.csv", "pml-train.csv")
download.file("https://d396qusza40orc.cloudfront.net/predmachlearn/pml-testing.csv", "pml-test.csv")

# Read data
train.orig <- read_csv("pml-train.csv")
train.orig$classe <- as.factor(train.orig$classe)
test.orig <- read_csv("pml-test.csv")

The training data consists of 19622 rows with 160 columns. There are 20 rows in the test set. The classe variable contains the following grades:

# Table of outcome 'classe'
table(train.orig$classe)
## 
##    A    B    C    D    E 
## 5580 3797 3422 3216 3607

Data cleanup

The training dataset contains 7 columns that does not provide informative data for predicting the training outcome: X1, user_name, raw_timestamp_part_1, raw_timestamp_part_2, cvtd_timestamp, new_window, num_window.

# Remove first 7 columns 
train <- train.orig
train <- train[, -c(1:7)]

In addition, there are 103 variables with a large number of missing (NA) values that we will ommit for further analysis:

# Explore missing data rows/cols
missing <- apply(train, 2, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
table(missing)
## missing
##     0     1 19216 19217 19218 19220 19221 19293 19294 
##    50     3    91     1     1     1     4     1     1
# Chop off columns with lots of missing data
excl.inds <- missing < 5
train <- train[, excl.inds]

There seems to be one row with 3 missing values. Delete row:

# Where are the other misisng data points?
excl.rows <- which(apply(train, 1, function(x) sum(is.na(x))) > 0)
train <- train[-excl.rows, ]

That leaves us with 52 predictor variables in the training dataset.

Data partitioning

For building the model we need a test set with known classe outcome variable. Letâs split the training set into a test and training set using the createDataPartition() function of the caret package:

# Split data set 
inTrain <- createDataPartition(y=train$classe, p=0.7, list=FALSE)
mytest <- train[-inTrain,]
train <- train[inTrain,]

This gives 5884 rows in the test set and 13737 rows in the final training set.

Model building

Set up a common trainControl object to use in all models we explore. We will use a 5-fold cross-validation in the following models.

# set up a trainControl object with 5-fold cross-validation
trc <- trainControl(method="cv", number=5)

Random forest

We start with exploring the random forest algorithm (provided with the ranger package):

# Ranom forrest
mod_rf <- train(classe ~ ., 
                method="ranger", data=train, 
                trControl=trc, 
                importance = 'impurity')
## Growing trees.. Progress: 97%. Estimated remaining time: 0 seconds.
# Predict on test data
pred_rf <- predict(mod_rf, mytest)

# Cross-table
table(pred_rf, mytest$classe)
##        
## pred_rf    A    B    C    D    E
##       A 1672    4    0    0    0
##       B    1 1135    6    0    0
##       C    0    0 1020    6    3
##       D    0    0    0  958    1
##       E    0    0    0    0 1078
# Calcualte confusion matrix
cm_rf <- confusionMatrix(pred_rf, mytest$classe)

This model provides an accuracy of 0.996. Thatâs pretty goodâ¦

Based on the random forest model we predict the 20 data points of the test set:

Exploring other models

Although the random forest model provides an accuracy of 0.996, we will check if other popular algorithms performs equivalently good under default settings:

Gradient Boosting

# Boosting
mod_gbm <- train(classe ~ .,
                 method="gbm", data=train, 
                 trControl=trc, verbose=FALSE)

pred_gbm <- predict(mod_gbm, mytest)
table(pred_gbm, mytest$classe)
##         
## pred_gbm    A    B    C    D    E
##        A 1648   39    0    1    1
##        B   20 1063   31    1   14
##        C    5   36  989   31   10
##        D    0    1    5  924   13
##        E    0    0    1    7 1044
cm_gbm <- confusionMatrix(pred_gbm, mytest$classe)
cm_gbm$overall["Accuracy"]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.9632903

Conclusion

Random forest seems to be an excellent model for predicting exercise manner with an accuracy of 0.996. k-NN gives an accuracy of 0.909 while gradient boosting gives an accuracy of 0.963.
